1. Customizing user parameters:

Creating a dictionary or map for passing emitter parameters can be a good way to make your system more flexible. Here's an example of how to implement this:

Create a struct to store the user parameter data:

```cpp
USTRUCT(BlueprintType)
struct FEmitterParameter
{
	GENERATED_BODY()

	UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly)
	FName ParameterName;

	UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly)
	float ParameterValue;
};
```

Next, create a map or a dictionary as a UPROPERTY in your Ability class to hold the emitter parameters:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Emitter")
	TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter> EmitterParameters;
```

When you pass the data to the Niagara Actor, you can update the Niagara Component's parameters:

```cpp
void ANiagaraAbilityActor::UpdateEmitterParameters(const TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter>& EmitterParameters)
{
	for (const auto& Param : EmitterParameters)
	{
		NiagaraComponent->SetScalarParameter(Param.Value.ParameterName, Param.Value.ParameterValue);
	}
}
```

This way, you can easily customize the parameters for each ability without hardcoding the individual parameter names, making it easier to add new parameters in the future.

2. Event-based communication:

In UE, event-based communication typically means using dynamic multicast delegates to notify subscribers about specific events occurring. In this context, you would use events to notify the Niagara Actor when specific changes are made in the Ability system.

Here's an example in C++:

Define a dynamic multicast delegate in your Ability class:

```cpp
DECLARE_DYNAMIC_MULTICAST_DELEGATE_OneParam(FOnEmitterParameterUpdated, const TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter>&, EmitterParameters);

UPROPERTY(BlueprintAssignable, Category = "Emitter")
	FOnEmitterParameterUpdated OnEmitterParameterUpdated;
```

In your Ability class, when there's a change in the emitter parameters, call this delegate:

```cpp
OnEmitterParameterUpdated.Broadcast(NewEmitterParameters);
```

In your Niagara Actor class, bind a function to this delegate. First, add a UFUNCTION to your Actor:

```cpp
UFUNCTION()
	void OnEmitterParametersUpdated(const TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter>& NewEmitterParameters);
```

Then, when you spawn the Niagara Actor, bind the function to the delegate:

```cpp
Ability->OnEmitterParameterUpdated.AddDynamic(this, &ANiagaraAbilityActor::OnEmitterParametersUpdated);
```

Finally, implement the function to update the Niagara component based on the new parameters:

```cpp
void ANiagaraAbilityActor::OnEmitterParametersUpdated(const TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter>& NewEmitterParameters)
{
	// Update the Niagara Component's parameters using the new data
}
```

This approach allows for efficient communication between the Ability system and the Niagara Actor while keeping them loosely coupled, making it easier to maintain and extend the system in the future.

To initialize and set up the emitter dictionary, first, create a function in your Ability class (C++). This function will receive a set of FEmitterParameters and add them to your EmitterParameters dictionary.

Here's an example of the function:

```cpp
UCLASS()
class YOURGAME_API AYourAbilityClass : public AActor
{
	GENERATED_BODY()

public:
	// ...

	UFUNCTION(BlueprintCallable, Category = "Emitter")
	void InitializeEmitterParameters(const TArray<FEmitterParameter>& Parameters);

protected:
	// ...

	UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Emitter")
	TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter> EmitterParameters;
};

void AYourAbilityClass::InitializeEmitterParameters(const TArray<FEmitterParameter>& Parameters)
{
	for (const FEmitterParameter& Param : Parameters)
	{
		EmitterParameters.Add(Param.ParameterName, Param);
	}
}
```

Then, in the editor or when creating a new instance of the Ability class, call the InitializeEmitterParameters function with the parameters specific to the ability you want to set up.

For example, if you have a Fireball ability that requires a float parameter named "FireballSpeed", you would initialize the dictionary like this:

```cpp
// Instantiate your ability (assuming you have an ability derived from AYourAbilityClass)
AYourAbilityClass* FireballAbility = GetWorld()->SpawnActor<AYourAbilityClass>(...);

// Create an FEmitterParameter for the FireballSpeed
FEmitterParameter FireballSpeed;
FireballSpeed.ParameterName = FName("FireballSpeed");
FireballSpeed.ParameterValue = 500.0f; // Set the speed value

// Initialize the ability's EmitterParameters
FireballAbility->InitializeEmitterParameters({ FireballSpeed });
```

This way, your EmitterParameters dictionary will be set up with the initial parameters required for the specific ability, and you can easily extend and modify it as needed.

If you don't know which ability you are using at compile time, you can create an Ability Factory to handle instantiating and initializing different types of ability classes.

Here are the steps for creating the Ability Factory:

1. In the Ability classes, set up a function to initialize their specific EmitterParameters.

`YourAbilityBaseClass.h`

```cpp
UCLASS()
class YOURGAME_API AYourAbilityBaseClass : public AActor
{
	GENERATED_BODY()

public:
	// ...

	virtual void InitializeEmitterParameters();

protected:
	UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Emitter")
	TMap<FName, FEmitterParameter> EmitterParameters;
};
```

2. In the Ability subclasses, override the InitializeEmitterParameters and set their specific EmitterParameters within the function.

`FireballAbility.h`

```cpp
UCLASS()
class YOURGAME_API AFireballAbility : public AYourAbilityBaseClass
{
	GENERATED_BODY()

public:
	// ...

	virtual void InitializeEmitterParameters() override;
};
```

`FireballAbility.cpp`

```cpp
void AFireballAbility::InitializeEmitterParameters()
{
	FEmitterParameter FireballSpeed;
	FireballSpeed.ParameterName = FName("FireballSpeed");
	FireballSpeed.ParameterValue = 500.0f;

	EmitterParameters.Add(FireballSpeed.ParameterName, FireballSpeed);
}
```

3. Create an enum to identify the different Ability types.

`AbilityType.h`

```cpp
UENUM(BlueprintType)
enum class EAbilityType : uint8
{
	Fireball,
	Heal,
	// Add other ability types here
};
```

4. Implement the Ability Factory.

`AbilityFactory.h`

```cpp
UCLASS()
class YOURGAME_API AAbilityFactory : public AActor
{
	GENERATED_BODY()

public:
	// ...

	UFUNCTION(BlueprintCallable, Category = "Abilities")
	static AYourAbilityBaseClass* CreateAbility(UObject* WorldContextObject, TSubclassOf<AYourAbilityBaseClass> AbilityClass);
};
```

`AbilityFactory.cpp`

```cpp
AYourAbilityBaseClass* AAbilityFactory::CreateAbility(UObject* WorldContextObject, TSubclassOf<AYourAbilityBaseClass> AbilityClass)
{
	UWorld* World = WorldContextObject->GetWorld();
	if (World == nullptr) return nullptr;

	AYourAbilityBaseClass* NewAbility = World->SpawnActor<AYourAbilityBaseClass>(AbilityClass);
	if (NewAbility)
	{
		NewAbility->InitializeEmitterParameters();
	}
	return NewAbility;
}
```

5. Finally, use the CreateAbility function from the Ability Factory to create a new instance of the desired Ability class.

```cpp
FActorSpawnParameters SpawnParams;
UObject* WorldContext = GetWorld();
TSubclassOf<AYourAbilityBaseClass> FireballClass = AFireballAbility::StaticClass();

// Spawning & initializing the Fireball ability by using the Ability Factory
AYourAbilityBaseClass* FireballAbility = AAbilityFactory::CreateAbility(WorldContext, FireballClass);
```

By using this approach, you can have more flexibility when dealing with abilities whose types are not known at compile time. The Ability Factory provides a standardized way to create and initialize abilities, keeping your code cleaner and more organized.

